give you a better, even a better perspective of how we manage our planning.

And it's still true today that we use the tool of a transportation plan to push most of our programs through, or at least get some sort of commitment from our city council, whether it be an ordinance or a resolution.
But you have to understand that the transportation planning division of the planning department has grown to encompass
an area-wide transportation planning designation by the governor.
And if you're a transportation planner, you'll understand that it means the Metropolitan Planning Organization.

That designation entails certain responsibilities to carry out transportation plans for all the local governments contained within our urbanized area, which is the city of Portland, the city of Corpus Christi, the county of San Patricio, and Nueces County.

In order to maintain that designation and eligibility to continue receiving transportation funds, we have to annually update our transportation plan and take it back before a policy advisory group, which consists of elected officials, to approve.
That in itself entails a commitment to do certain things.
And because the Metropolitan Planning Organization, which I'm in charge of, includes other governments,
It leaves our own administration no choice but to follow for the most part my recommendations on moving forward with approval of some kind of planning document.
And we have in my transportation program that I put together, I'm talking about the planning program that I put together, I always include two major elements and those elements

have to do with the other elements of a transportation plan, of a comprehensive plan, socioeconomic work, land use, utilities, et cetera, because transportation plans are not effective unless they're developed and consistent with the other planning elements and that realization.
In addition, the fact that because money is becoming so short, scarce, I should say, the utilization of that money in the most efficient manner
It's extremely critical to continue to allow this city to grow in an orderly fashion.

And I believe people have come to realize that an understanding what's going to happen five years from now, ten years from now, is necessary in order to allocate those funds for those kinds of improvements.
A major street that we want to put in, which is the extension, major highways, extension of a freeway facility, once it begins from the planning stage,
until its final construction could take as much as 20 years.
And unfortunately, what happens there in the interim could be disastrous.
But until we move now, we know that that facility, the sooner we start, the better off we are.
The same is true for understanding what our growth patterns are and what our sewer needs are going to be, our drainage needs are going to be, our water needs are going to be.
We've got to start now to start putting these things to the ground.
I think the management has a realization that information is very critical.

And I think that we'll see eventually not only what I consider a sort of an unofficial approval of what we're doing as far as long-range or as comprehensive planning or development planning, but we may ultimately even see an official
approval of some sort of comprehensive document, which has taken us so many years to move towards that.
And I've been here 10 years.

The zoning ordinance was looked upon as our plan, and comprehensive plans were really good for looking at and dreaming about and nothing that they could actually, that the council or the city management wanted to work with.
From that point of view to where we're beginning to transition to a wider acceptance of the need for long-range planning, if we have to change the name of it,
to something that's more acceptable, we'll do that as long as the end results are the same.
It really doesn't matter to me.
This also reinforces the fact that changes, particularly if they're going to be good, in my opinion, have to occur slowly, particularly in this community.
This city has been very anti-change for the most part.
And now, over the last three years, it's extremely pro-development.
And I think that new concept of progress is having influences working its way back into our own work programs, our own efforts.
One of the things we anticipate is an accelerated growth across this area.
We think that the city of Houston, which we have lost so many people to,
that it's going to be maxing itself out as far as growth is concerned in the next four to five years.
And that Corpus is sort of like a sleeping bear getting ready to awake.
And it does have a lot of potential for handling major growth, both in all areas of the city.
It's a very long city.
And of course, in fact, we have a very aggressive annexation policy recently, although

Corpus Christi also includes all the Bay Area, and we just recently annexed a major portion of the island, and I think we intend to move forward and annex the rest of the Bay Area island up to the city limits of Port Aransas.
And not in the northwest part of town.
We're seeing a tremendous amount of growth there.
We might end up being the longest city in the state of Texas where it's going.
